ce:section.ce:para:
UV–vis absorption and normalized PL spectra were recorded to explore the optical properties of A-GQDs and U-GQDs. Prime quality N-GQDs were produced by optimizing the reaction conditions, such as reaction time and the quota of reactants [41,42,48]. Fig. 4
                        A–B shows the optical properties of A-GQDs at the same reaction time (10 h) and diverse component proportions. The material ratios (1:5; 1:10; 1:12.5; 1:15, g: mL) of A-GQDs had a significant effect on UV–vis absorbance and PL intensity. At the same time, the reaction ratio of carbon source and nitrogen source will also affect the optical performance of the materials. When the proportion of nitrogen source is small, the amount of nitrogen doping is low, and the fluorescence intensity is low. As the composition increases, the amount of doped nitrogen increases, and the fluorescence intensity increases. When the amount of nitrogen source is further increased, the amount of doped nitrogen does not continue to increase, and the PL intensity is basically remains stable. The optical properties of A-GQDs at identical material ratios (1:10/g/mL) and various reaction times are displayed in Fig. 4D–E. The A-GQDs with various reaction time (6 h; 8 h; 10 h; 12 h; 14 h) also had a significant impact on UV–vis absorption and PL intensity. As far as the reaction time is concerned, the reaction time is too short, and the substance only undergoes polymerization without further carbonization. As the reaction time increases, the materials will undergo carbonization to form fluorescent N-GQDs. Further prolonging the reaction time will make the carbonization too high and the N-GQDs will grow up or agglomerate, resulting in a decrease in PL intensity. Thus, the optimum material ratio of CA and ammonia and reaction time were 1:10 (g/mL) and 10 h, respectively. The QY of GQDs varied with the fabrication method and the surface chemistry involved. The QY was measured by using quinine sulfate as a standard, with excitation wavelength set to 360 nm. The optimal QY of A-GQDs was 45.4 % based on the above optimal conditions and considering the practical application problems (Fig. 4C and F). The UV–vis absorbance, PL emission intensity, and QY of U-GQDs prepared at different molar ratios are shown in Fig. 4G–I. The molar ratio of CA and urea changed from 1:10 to 15:10 (mol: mol), and the QY of U-GQDs was more than 50 %. The UV–vis absorbance, PL emission intensity, and QY of U-GQDs prepared at different reaction time (2 h; 4 h; 6 h; 8 h; 10 h) are shown in Fig. 4J–L. Proper molar ratio and reaction time promote the formation of fluorescent U-GQDs. The optimum ratio of CA and urea was 9:10 and appropriate reaction time is 4 h, and the QY of U-GQDs reached 54 %. Compared with the QY (0.75 %) of GQDs-CA, A-GQDs and U-GQDs showed higher fluorescence intensity and QY, revealing that doping N can certainly promote the QY of GQDs [48] (Table 4
                        ). However, the slightly higher QY of U-GQDs than that of A-GQDs is probably because of the higher nitrogen doping degree and graphene-like crystal structure, which is in good agreement with the nitrogen composition in the full XPS spectra. Correspondingly, the QY of U-GQDs increased significantly.

GQDs were synthesized using other carbon sources such as graphene oxide (GO), glucose, glutamic acid, and starch, under the same hydrothermal route to better optimize the experimental factors. Table 4 shows the PL intensity and QY of N-GQDs prepared from different carbon sources. The fluorescence intensities of GQDs-GO [54], GQDs-glucose [17], GQDs-glutamic acid [55], GQDs-starch [16], and GQDs-CA [56,57] were 3.2, 2.8, 2.3, 4, 0.6, and 0.28, and the QYs were 10.65 %, 6.98 %, 4.90 %, 1.24 %, and 0.75 %, respectively. Compared with other carbon sources, CA as a carbon source shows lower fluorescence intensity and QY but can self-assemble into flake structure and dehydrate to form a graphene framework. The more hydroxyl and carboxyl functional groups in the structure, the easier it is to condense with the amino group, and the higher the doping degree of nitrogen, the higher the fluorescence intensity and QY. Given all these factors, CA was selected as carbon source. N-GQDs were synthesized using all types of nitrogen sources, such as ammonia, Tris-HMA, urea, ethanolamine, and thiourea, to investigate the effects of N source types (Table 5
                        ). GQDs-ammonia, GQDs-Tris-HMA [44], and GQDs-urea had higher PL QY of 45.4 %, 46.8 %, and 54 %, respectively, compared with GQDs-ethanolamine and GQDs-thiourea. Nitrogen doping introduces a new surface state labeled as the N-state that strongly affects the PL QY of GQDs. The effect of reaction solvents on the fluorescence intensity and QY of N-GQDs was investigated [11], as described in Table 6
                        . Different solvents, such as water and DMF, had minimal effect on the fluorescence intensity and QY of N-GQDs prepared with Tris as nitrogen source. However, N-GQDs prepared with urea as nitrogen source had opposite results. GQDs prepared with DMF redshifted at the PL emission peak, and their PL intensity was disordered. From the above results, CA can be used as carbon source because it is easy to dehydrate between molecules to form a graphene framework. Under the action of nitrogen source, amides are formed by dehydration and condensation of −COOH and −NH2. More nitrogen enters the graphene skeleton with continuous reaction, completing the preparation of N-GQDs. This is a summary of the overall optical properties of various materials in Figure S1. The high PL QY of N-GQDs can be obtained by using CA as carbon source and ammonia, Tris-HMA, and urea as N source. Considering the green, cost and benefit, N-GQDs were prepared by using water as the reaction solvent.
